RMarkdown setup

library(knitr)
knitr::opts_chunk$set(cache = TRUE, cache.lazy = FALSE, warning=FALSE,
                      fig.width=6, fig.height=6, autodep=TRUE)

Build the fault geometry

Note that with 1 km elements and set up as below, rupture would not propagate away from nucleation region. Currently using 400 m elements.

rundir = "TPV14"
system(paste("mkdir -p", rundir))

# through fault
x0 = 0
y0 = 0
z0 = 0
L = 28e3
W = 15e3
l = w = 400
nl = round(L/l)
nw = round(W/w)
strike = 0
dip = 90
rake = 180
ddot = 0
sectNum = 1

system2("/Users/dinger/RSQSim.github.master/BuildFaultModels/singlePlanarFault",
        args=c(x0, y0, z0, L, W, nl, nw, strike, dip, rake, ddot, sectNum),
        stdout=file.path(rundir, "fault1.flt"))

# branch fault

x0 = 0
y0 = 16e3
z0 = 0
L = 12e3
nl = round(L/l)
nw = round(W/w)
strike = 30
sectNum = 2
system2("/Users/dinger/RSQSim.github.master/BuildFaultModels/singlePlanarFault",
        args=c(x0, y0, z0, L, W, nl, nw, strike, dip, rake, ddot, sectNum),
        stdout=file.path(rundir, "fault2.flt"))

system2("cat", args=c(file.path(rundir, "fault1.flt"),
                      file.path(rundir, "fault2.flt")),
        stdout=file.path(rundir, "faults.flt"))

system2("rm", args=c(file.path(rundir, "fault1.flt"),
                     file.path(rundir, "fault2.flt")))

flt = readFault(file.path(rundir, "faults.flt"))

Set up initial stresses

Note that the 3 km x 3 km nucleation region centered on \(y\) = 8 km, \(z\) = -7.5 km may or may not fit exactly in a mesh with a given side length.

sigma = rep(120, flt$np)
write(sigma, file=file.path(rundir, "initSigma.txt"), ncol=1)

tau = rep(70, flt$np)
ynuc = 8e3
znuc = -7500
wnuc = 1500
nuc = which(flt$iseg == 1 & abs(flt$z - znuc) <= wnuc & abs(flt$y - ynuc) <= wnuc)
tau[nuc] = 81.6
write(tau, file=file.path(rundir, "initTau.txt"), ncol=1)

Elastic modulii

TPV14 (and TPV15) use \(\rho = 2670 \mathrm{kg}/\mathrm{m}^3\), \(V_s\) = 3464 m/s, and \(V_p\) = 6000 m/s. RSQSim needs the Lame parameters \(\lambda\) and \(\mu\). In terms of the density and wave speeds these are

\[\begin{align} \mu &= \rho V_s^2 \\ \lambda &= \rho \left( V_p^2 - 2V_s^2 \right) \end{align}\] 
rho = 2670
Vs = 3464
Vp = 6000

lameMu = rho * Vs*Vs / 1e6 # in MPa
lameLambda = rho * (Vp*Vp - 2*Vs*Vs) / 1e6

Friction parameters and initial state

We will use our usual fixed values of \(V^\mathrm{EQ}\) (though will definitely want to try variable \(V^\mathrm{EQ}\) eventually) of 1 m/s, \(V^\ast\) of \(10^{-6}\) m/s, \(D_c\) of \(10^{-5}\) m, \(a\) of 0.01, and \(b\) of 0.015. Then we will choose \(\mu_0\), and \(\theta_0\) from the two equations in http://rsqsim.ucr.edu/wiki/index.php/Stress_drops_in_artificially_nucleated_events#Further_attempt_at_more_accurate_estimate_of:

\[\begin{align} \mu_0 &= \frac{\tau_f}{\sigma} + \left(b-a\right)\ln\left(\frac{V^\mathrm{EQ}}{V^\ast}\right) \\ \theta_0 &= \left(\frac{D_c}{V^\ast}\right)^\frac{b-a}{b-a+a^\prime} \left(\frac{l b \sigma}{G V^\mathrm{EQ}}\right)^\frac{a^\prime}{b-a+a^\prime} \exp\left(\frac{\tau_p/\sigma - \mu_0}{b -a +a^\prime}\right) \end{align}\]

And then force the nucleation region to fail immediately at its initial shear stress level by lowering \(\theta\) there by the appropriate amount. RSQSim can do that automatically, but I’ll just calculate the numbers here and write out an initial \(\theta\) file instead.

For TPV14 (and TPV15) we have that \(\tau_p = \mu_s \sigma = 0.677 \cdot 120 \mbox{ MPa} = 81.24 \mbox{ MPa}\) and \(\tau_f = \mu_d \sigma = 0.525 \cdot 120 \mbox{ MPa} = 63 \mbox{ MPa}\). And therefore the peculiar \(\Delta\tau\) that I use in those formulas is 81.24 MPa - 63 MPa = 18.24 MPa.

mus = 0.677
mud = 0.525
taup = mus * sigma[1]
tauf = mud * sigma[1]

VEQ = 1.22 # adjusted from 1.0 to match rupture times in dynamic rupture models
Vstar = 1e-6
Dc = 1e-5
a = 0.01
fa = 0.1
aprime = fa*a
b = 0.015

mu0 = (tauf - 2.6)/sigma[1] + (b-a)*log(VEQ/Vstar) # offset estimated from initial runs...
theta0 = (Dc/Vstar)^((b-a)/(b-a+aprime)) * ((l*b*sigma[1])/(lameMu*VEQ))^((aprime)/(b-a+aprime)) *
          exp( (taup/sigma[1] - mu0)/(b - a + aprime) )

theta.nuc = RStheta(Vstar, mu0, taup, sigma[1], a, b, VEQ, Dc)

theta = rep(theta0, flt$np)
theta[nuc] = theta.nuc
write(theta, file=file.path(rundir, "initTheta.txt"))

So this gives \(\mu_0 = 0.57\) and \(\theta_0 = 3.5\) yrs. These seem somewhat reasonable.

Initial RSQSim parameter file

unlink("eqs..out")
system2("/Users/dinger/RSQSim.github.master/runRSQSim", stdout=NULL, stderr=NULL)
eqs = readEqs("eqs..out", saveRData=FALSE)
## [1] "Warning: /Users/dinger/Proposals/2019SCEC-branch/SCEC_CVS/faults.in doesn't exist"
unlink(c("eqs..out", "eqs..out.RData", ".Screen.Time.out", ".times_saved.out"))
params = eqs$params
rm(eqs)

params$A_1 = 0.01
params$B_1 = 0.015
params$Dc_1 = 1e-5
params$mu0_1 = mu0
params$ddotStar_1 = Vstar
params$alpha_1 = 0.25
params$theta0_1 = theta0
params$ddotEQ_1 = VEQ
params$lameLambda = lameLambda
params$lameMu = lameMu
params$nEq = 1
params$faultFname = "faults.flt"
params$outFnameInfix = "TPV14.run1"
params$writeTau = 2
params$writeSigma = 2
params$initTauFname = "initTau.txt"
params$initSigmaFname = "initSigma.txt"
params$initThetaFname = "initTheta.txt"

writeRSQSimInputFile(params, file.path(rundir, "TPV14.run1.in"))

Run external to .Rmd file, for now.

Rupture contour plots moved to below for easier comparison. Here just checking peak and final stresses.

eqs = readEqs(file.path(rundir, "eqs.TPV14.run1.out"))

hist(eqs$taupList, breaks="FD")

c(mean(eqs$taupList), taup)
## [1] 81.18439 81.24000
tauf.rsq = readFaultVal(eqs, val="tau", writeVal="final")$val[1,]
hist(tauf.rsq, breaks="FD")

c(mean(tauf.rsq), tauf)
## [1] 62.84159 63.00000

Move branch fault away from main fault as in actual TPV14

Easiest way to do this is to pin first column of elements on branch fault that is adjacent to main fault. Need to watch for rounding issues, but with 400 m elements, looks like just sorting on \(y\) coord will work.

pin = rep(0, eqs$fault$np)
pin[which(eqs$fault$iseg == 2 & eqs$fault$y == min(eqs$fault$y[eqs$fault$iseg == 2]))] = 1
write(pin, file=file.path(rundir, "pinned.run2.txt"), ncol=1)
params = eqs$params
params$outFnameInfix = "TPV14.run2"
params$pinnedFname = "pinned.run2.txt"
writeRSQSimInputFile(params, file.path(rundir, "TPV14.run2.in"))

100 m set off

Actual TPV14 uses “one element” set off, as I do above, but with 100 m elements. Here I will set off the branch fault by 100 m.

# through fault
x0 = 0
y0 = 0
z0 = 0
L = 28e3
W = 15e3
l = w = 400
nl = round(L/l)
nw = round(W/w)
strike = 0
dip = 90
rake = 180
ddot = 0
sectNum = 1

system2("/Users/dinger/RSQSim.github.master/BuildFaultModels/singlePlanarFault",
        args=c(x0, y0, z0, L, W, nl, nw, strike, dip, rake, ddot, sectNum),
        stdout=file.path(rundir, "run3.fault1.flt"))

# branch fault

setoff = 100
strike = 30
x0 = setoff * sin(strike*pi/180)
y0 = 16e3 + setoff * cos(strike*pi/180)
z0 = 0
L = 12e3
nl = round(L/l)
nw = round(W/w)
sectNum = 2
system2("/Users/dinger/RSQSim.github.master/BuildFaultModels/singlePlanarFault",
        args=c(x0, y0, z0, L, W, nl, nw, strike, dip, rake, ddot, sectNum),
        stdout=file.path(rundir, "run3.fault2.flt"))

system2("cat", args=c(file.path(rundir, "run3.fault1.flt"),
                      file.path(rundir, "run3.fault2.flt")),
        stdout=file.path(rundir, "run3.flt"))

system2("rm", args=c(file.path(rundir, "run3.fault1.flt"),
                     file.path(rundir, "run3.fault2.flt")))

flt3 = readFault(file.path(rundir, "run3.flt"))

params = eqs$params
params$outFnameInfix = "TPV14.run3"
params$faultFname = "run3.flt"
writeRSQSimInputFile(params, file.path(rundir, "TPV14.run3.in"))

Note that don’t need to mess with initial stresses, \(\theta\), etc.; these are the same as in run1.

As before, run RSQSim outside of .Rmd file.
